title: Mini DV frame for DVD spindle

description.text:
A small frame that holds Mini DV tape cases upright, 4 around, on to at least a 50 DVD spindle. with room for a few more disks. The "Full" is a CD sized, cd thin disk. this one offers a suggestion of alignment, the tapes will topple if jostled. It uses more plastic, but it looks better. The "Less" is a (better) trimmed down circle, much thicker, and small print bed friendly. The tapes are fairly rigidly upright. -
This is for easier archiving, as the computer backups are probably down to blue ray or DVD, but the master tapes still exist.

The ends might curl on the small one, but it gets thick enough to stop.
a practical concern is to keep less above or these on top.
on a 50, I suggest the few disks that it has space for go on top.
on a 100, put the tapes on top. with a blank or lesser important one as the buffer. the weight shouldnt matter, but depending on the enviornment (which would wreck your disks anyways) the pinpoint weight 'may' damage the top disk, but only after years or extreme temps. (dvdr's just arn't any good after 4 years, I found this out the hard way, even in a stable environment)
The frame itself support no weight, only the polycarbonate tape cases.

description.text: Form for a Rogowski coil. Useful for measuring the net current passing through the loop. This particular coil form was used to acquire data that was ultimately published in RSI, thereby proving the value of my home 3D printing hobby. (That is, it has some nonzero value. Costs are a totally different thing.) To learn more about what this thing is used for, see http://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rogowski_coil.

Print out both halves, lay your wire in the depression along the major axis of one half of the form, put the other half of the form on top, and then loop the rest of the wire back around the guides on the minor axis.  Use epoxy to hold the form together if your wire is floppy or loose.

description.text: The Parallella cluster stack packs 144 processors and 200 GFlops into a space of approximately 150x86x54mm. A veritable supercomputer on a desktop While the Epiphany processors are very low power, the Zynq FPGAs hosting the ARM cores and glue logic get warm and need cooling. This design provides a holder for two 120mm fans to force air across the FPGA heat sinks of the entire stack. The design is configurable (through epiphany-paramaters.scad) to allow for different size fans. The original source is on GitHub: https://github.com/jeremybennett/scad-examples.

In our version the fans are 25cm thick and fixed using M3x40 bolts. The stack is fixed to the base using M3x8 bolts. Some fans have grill covers, and these will need spacers to match the thickness of the lugs on the base. These can be printed from epiphany-spacer.scad (you'll probably need 4).

This thing has moved to Youmagine: https://www.youmagine.com/designs/squeezebox-amplifer-power-switch This project makes a power switch to control an amplifier connected to a Squeezebox. The switch turns the mains power on and off when the Squeezebox is turned on an off.

This box needs some care and attention to print perfectly because it's very wide and not very tall. If you're not careful, the corners will peel upwards and warp the shape of the box. Since the electronics aren't at all packed in, this probably won't matter too much if it happens. Also, get ready for some long prints - even the lid took about two and a half hours on my Ultimaker. For details about the electronics to go inside, take a look at http://electronicsfordogs.com/articles/control-amplifier-squeezebox Depeding how you make the electronics, you may need to move some of the holes around. I've included the Sketchup source file so you can do this.

This is a very simple end cap for knitting needles. You should be able to print out a pair of them relatively quickly and use a string to hold them onto your knitting project

• Print out 2 end caps.
  • Print 1 string holder.
  • Run the string through the end caps, then run each end of the string through the string holder. This should allow you to expand and cinch the string onto the needles.

Do you need a specific birthday candle?? Usually you can only find the numbers that you don't need (Murphy's Law)?
Here's your solution. You can use the typical thin candles with a customized number as the base.

If you want to print directly the .stl, it's ready to do it (candle diameter: 5.6-5.7 mm) But if you need to change something (as the diameter, the size or the base position) make sure you follow these steps:
  • Change "/Users/Nicuma/ooml_creations/Number_candle/" in the code to your own directory.
  • Change the .dxf file directory to your own directory too, or save it in the same location as your building folder.
    • Enjoy it!!! I did it! (Today it's my birthday! ^^ So I printed them, and they work perfectly.)

I made the code in C++, using the new realased OOML 2.0 library (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:17761 iearobotics.com/oomlwiki). So, If you want to change some of the parameters (dimensions) or work with this code to make some derivated or new desings, you should download this libray. Afterwards, you only have to open the .cpp and change it. I also add the OpenScad generated code; however, I think it isn't very intuitive to change.

I found that it was very tight and drew it to have a minor convex on the top, a little wider and shorter, and there is a very small curve in on the inside to help it "snap" into place. (Kinda works). Otherwise it's awesome. I will try to figure out a nice way to let more light through in the future.  Let me know what you guys think!
